</task><concept class="- topic/topic concept/concept " id="unique_2" topicrefclass="- map/topicref " nd:nd-id="what_is_bmi" oid="what_is_bmi" specializations="@props/deliveryTarget">
    <title class="- topic/title "><ph class="- topic/ph topic/title-wrapper ">What is BMI ?</ph></title>
    <shortdesc class="- topic/shortdesc ">Body Mass Index (BMI) is a simple and widely used method to estimate an individual's
        body fat based on their weight with respect to their height. It’s commonly used by
        healthcare professionals to evaluate the risk of developing health conditions related to
        body weight, such as obesity, diabetes, hypertension, cardiovascular diseases, and certain
        types of cancer. It provides numerical values that are catergorized into different ranges,
        indicating whether they are underweight,normal weight, overweight, or obese.</shortdesc>
    <conbody class="- topic/body  concept/conbody ">
        <ul class="- topic/ul " id="unique_2_Connect_42_ul_dwy_2wd_zcc" nd:nd-id="ul_dwy_2wd_zcc">
            <li class="- topic/li ">Underweight: BMI &lt; 18.5</li>
            <li class="- topic/li ">Normal Weight: BMI 18.5–24.9</li>
            <li class="- topic/li ">Overweight: BMI 25–29.9</li>
            <li class="- topic/li ">Obese: BMI &gt;= 30</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="- topic/p "><b class="+ topic/ph hi-d/b ">Formula to calculate BMI:</b></p>
        <p class="- topic/p ">BMI (standard units) = Weight (kg)/Height (m)sq</p>
        <p class="- topic/p ">BMI (imperial units) = Weight (lbs)*703/Height (in)sq</p>
    </conbody>
